### **System Architecture** {#system-architecture}

**10 sec. summary**: Users \-\> \[client\] \-\> Rest API \-\> Airflow DAG \-\> Databricks Workflow \-\> Dispatch

#### **Overview** {#overview}

* [Deep Dive on 2024-02-07](https://yipitdata.zoom.us/rec/share/8Y6C2tJAQueyRRyp24ci1wCnrpcXxtk1JFV5vnFquv9dky0ly88OPeHorFX-lLhZ.t3EkkGOjnPgtl_P7)   
* Passcode: 89ZS9\#Y\*

#### **Core Concepts** {#core-concepts}

* A SKU ("product") is a group of deliverables  
  * Each deliverable is a function of:  
    * Source or input tables  
    * Query template  
    * Collection of query parameters  
    * Output table  
    * Output table type (incremental, batch, PIT)  
    * Tags  
    * QA tests  
  * Deliverables are instances of parent data models ("FPModel")  
    * Given deliverables are iterated on during a product life cycle, we retain versions of deliverables ("FPModelVersions") that are distinct records in the Freeport database  
    * Deliverable versions are the primary integration point for apps external to Freeport  
* Deliverables are only configurations, need to persist deliverable content for clients to consume (a.k.a. FPMaterialization)  
  * Each FPMaterialization is a function of:  
    * A model version  
    * Source table version(s)  
    * Scheduling flags (release time and allow release)

##### **Freeport Ontology** {#freeport-ontology}

Core models for Freeport processing are below. 

| Django Name | Common Name | Description | Dependency |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| FPModel | \- | Parent Resource for a Deliverable (a.k.a. Data Model) | \- |
| FPModelVersion | Deliverable | An instance of a data model with a specific configuration Maps 1:1 with Dispatch Deliverable  Each latest major model version will be an active Dispatch deliverable | FPModel (FK), FPQueryTemplateVersion (FK) |
| FPMaterialization | Materialization | The event of persisting data to the target table of a Data Model Version, i.e. a new target table version | FPModelVersion (FK) |
| FPRelease | Release | The event of distributing a specific materialization to clients via Dispatch | FPMaterialization (FK) |
| FPModelGroup | Model Group | Group of FPModels that are managed together  | FPModel (M2M) |
| FPModelVersionGroup | Deliverable Group | Group of FPModelVersionss that are managed together and belongs to a FPModelGroup | FPModelGroup (FK) FPModelVersion (M2M) |
| FPMaterializationGroup | Materialization Group | Group of FPMaterializations that belong to an FPModelVersionGroup (event of processing data for the model version group) | FPModelVersionGroup (FK) FPMaterialization (M2M) |
| FPReleaseGroup | Release Group | Group of FPReleases that belong to the FPMaterializationGroup (event of releasing multiple materializations together) | FPMaterializationGroup (FK) FPRelease (M2M) |
| FPTarget | Output Table | Reference to a FP managed table that houses the data generated from materializations | FPModelVersion (FK) |
| FPTargetVersion | Output Table Version | Reference to specific delta version of an FPTarget and associated tables stats | FPTarget (FK), FPMaterialization (FK) |
| FPSource | Input Table | Reference to the input tables for a FPModel version | FPModelVersion (M2M) |
| FPSourceVersion | Input Table Version | Reference to specific delta version of an FPSource used in Materializations | FPSource (FK), FPMaterialization (M2M) |
| FPQueryTemplate | \- | Parent Query template record  | \- |
| FPQueryTemplateVersion | Query Template | Instance of an FPQueryTemplate that includes a specific Jinja template to produce SQL queries.  These are used by FPModelVersion and FPMaterializations to populate output tables (FPTarget) | FPQueryTemplate (FK) |

##### **Versioning Mechanics** {#versioning-mechanics}

* `FPModelVersions` have semantic versioning applied (0.0.0)  
  * **Data major version**: Incremented for every breaking schema change (ex: new columns not at end of schema, column type changes, output table name changes)  
  * **Data minor version**: Incremented for every non-breaking schema change (ex: new columns at end of schema)  
  * **Patch version**: Incremented for any other change  
  * Deliverables in Dispatch are named by the model version title \+ data major version  
  * Versoning is generated as part of the model version DAG  
* `FPModelVersionGroups` have semantic versioning applied (0.0.0)  
  * **Data major version**: Incremented whenever an FPModelVersion has a major version change or is removed from the group (i.e. "breaking" change for a group)  
  * **Data minor version**: Incremented whenever a FPModelVersion has a minor version change or a deliverable is added to the group (i.e. "minor" change for a group)  
  * **Patch version**: Incremented for any other change to the deliverables in the group or the group itself  
  * Versoning is generated as part of the model version group DAG

#### **REST API** {#rest-api}

* All actions in Freeport is via the API  
  * Ex: creating a model, model version, materialization, release  
  * The API will asynchronously trigger a DAG run to process model versions, materializations, and releases.  
    * GET endpoints will reveal the status of the dag run in the `airflow_status` column  
  * Users will not create a releases directly, this is done through Dispatch  
* API is generally immutable, only get/posts allowed with the exception of materialization schedule  
  * POST requests will validate inputs and see if a matching resource is available. If so it will return a 400 saying a duplicate resource already exists

##### **Debugging** {#debugging}

* Use Sentry to see any non-400 level exceptions  
* Can log into Django admin and see the specific model version/materialization that failed. Usually the issue will be related to the Airflow DAG run (use the Airflow Run URL link to navigate to it)  
  * Runs that are over 25-runs in the past will not display with the airflow run url directly. To navigate to these, fetch airflow\_url from fp admin:  
    * [https://freeport-service-prod.yipit.systems/admin/data\_model/fpmaterialization/93418/change/](https://freeport-service-prod.yipit.systems/admin/data_model/fpmaterialization/93418/change/)  
    * https://freeport-airflow-prod.yipit.systems/dags/fp\_data\_model\_materialization/grid?dag\_run\_id=manual\_\_2024-06-17T14%3A17%3A17.732299%2B00%3A00\&tab=graph  
  * The above airflow link won't work because it's too far in the past.  
  * Navigate to airflow link anyway in order to get to the right dag, then adjust filters:  
    * set timestamp to right after the time of the airflow run  
    * set num\_runs to 100 to give yourself a nice buffer  
  * Copy the query params in the url:  
    * \&base\_date=2024-06-17T15%3A01%3A31Z\&num\_runs=100  
  * Add these query params to the airflow link:  
    * https://freeport-airflow-prod.yipit.systems/dags/fp\_data\_model\_materialization/grid?dag\_run\_id=manual\_\_2024-06-17T14%3A17%3A17.732299%2B00%3A00\&tab=graph\&base\_date=2024-06-17T15%3A01%3A31Z\&num\_runs=100

* Replay API calls using databricks notebook ([freeport\_client](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/baaa52d72289285114592a50e1a425836f494772/freeport_databricks/client/api_client.py#L138-L183))

#### **Airflow**  {#airflow}

* Freeports Airflow installation is as an asynchronous process flow for the REST API  
* DAGs exist for the following REST API endpoints  
  * POST FPModelVersion: ModelVersion DAG  
  * POST FPModelVersionGroup: ModelVersionGroup DAG  
  * POST FPMaterialization: Materialization DAG  
  * POST FPMaterializationGroup: MaterializationGroup DAG  
  * POST FPRelease: Release DAG  
* DAGs are responsible for the following operations  
  * Fetch the relevant data for the associated FPModelVersion/FPMaterialization/FPRelease from the FP backend  
  * Process any data as related to the resource in Databricks as a workflow run  
  * Update the the associated FPModelVersion/FPMaterialization/FPRelease for any missing fields and mark airflow\_status="complete"  
  * Make API calls to Dispatch to register deliverables and deferred publications  
  * Send email summaries of FP events

##### **Debugging** {#debugging-1}

* Airflow Error emails summarize the error and have links to the associate DAG run  
  * These are sent to [freeport@yipitdata.com](mailto:freeport@yipitdata.com), join the google group if you want access  
  * Filter out materialization completion emails as these can be noisy  
* Use the logs tab for a given Airflow task within a DAG run to identify error details. Multiple tabs might be there for each attempt of the task  
* If there is a databricks specific error, the airflow error emails will provide a link to the databricks  job run URL. Best place to look if if there is an error  
* Safe to trigger a new model version/materialization if there is an error.   
  * However a repair of the run by "clearing" the failed task might be a quicker workaround. When clearing think about the implications, ex: the user may have already seen a failure and it will not update the status automatically unless they re-run their operation  
  * Some actions are not idempotent, ex: API calls to Dispatch. This may prevent us from using the clear task strategy unless other cleanup actions are taken  
  * Some actions may need to be made after the DAG run was cleared and successful. Ex: a downstream DAG in dispatch also needs to be repaired after a release is repaired successfully.

###### *Implementation for Single FPModelVersion* {#implementation-for-single-fpmodelversion}

* Fetches `FPModelVersion` from backend using a virtualenv python task.   
  * Model Version ID to retrieve is specified in DAG run conf  
  * Model version details stored in as an XCOM value   
* Check if the model version is already complete. If yes, skip to completion of DAG with no processing  
  * Completion state is determined by the `airflow_status` field equal to `success`  
* If model version is not complete, set the deployment\_name (i.e. workspace of the DAG) and upload the model version configuration to a S3 location  
  * Configuration is later retrieved inside a databricks job run using the UC API \- this is to avoid parameter size limits with the databricks jobs api  
  * airflow\_status is set to running here  
* Run databricks workflow for [model version](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/develop/freeport_databricks/workflows/materialization/00_perisist_fp_model_version_details.py). Workflow run will:  
  * Execute in a workspace based on the deployment\_name  
  * Retrieve model version configuration from S3  
  * Validate SQL syntax of query template \+ parameters  
  * Validate output table schema based on `allow_major_version` and `allow_minor_version` flags  
  * Generate and return the output table schema as a json object for the run  
* If workflow is successful, process the `FPModelVersion` in the Freeport backend ([task code](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/8a9e8e824ec63561570211e31e98f1d0bc8263cc/freeport_airflow/dags/custom/webapp/freeport_service_operator.py#L152))  
  * Retrieve notebook output from job run (i.e. the output table schema) and saves them as `FPField` objects   
  * Assign the model version's semantic version (major\_version, minor\_version, patch\_version)  
  * Record the model version with airflow\_status=success  
  * If `FPModel.enable_in_dispatch`, Freeport will request the creation of the Dispatch deliverable  
    * Assigns `FPModelVersionTagValue` record that links the `FPModelVersion` to the dispatch `deliverable_id` \- **Note**: this is important as this is how dispatch API calls are made in subsequent areas of Freeport  
* If the databricks workflow or any other airflow tasks fail, mark the `FPModelVersion` as a failure in the app backend  
  * Sets the airflow\_status=failed

###### *Implementation for FPModelVersionGroup* {#implementation-for-fpmodelversiongroup}

* Fetches `FPModelVersionGroup` from backend using a virtualenv python task.   
  * Model Version Group ID to retrieve is specified in DAG run conf  
  * Model version group configuration stored in as an XCOM value   
* If there is an earlier FPModelVersionGroup for a given FPModelGroup that is not yet complete/failed, the DAG run waits until those are complete  
  * This is needed to handle race conditions given how users might trigger creation of these groups repeatedly from Databricks  
* Start processing of the group  
  * Set group airflow\_status=running  
* Isolate each `FPModelVersion` configuration from the group and trigger a parallel, child DAG run for each \- same DAG to process as the individual FPModelVersion  
  * The Group DAG run waits for successful completion of each child dag run  
  * Each child dag run is triggered in order of the depends\_on value for the FPModelVersion within the group. This dependency logic is managed within the Group Dag run ([task](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/8a9e8e824ec63561570211e31e98f1d0bc8263cc/freeport_airflow/dags/custom/webapp/group_processing.py#L591-L693))  
* Once all model versions are successful, the group is marked as airflow\_status=success  in the DAG run and the run is complete

###### *Common Errors* {#common-errors}

* Query syntax error for FPModelVersion  
* FPModelVersion invalid schema change due to allow\_major\_version or allow\_minor\_version  
* Child model version fails due to a dependent model version failing  
* InvalidBumpVersionException (shouldn't see this anymore) \- occurs if there is some ModelVersionChange that is not tracked in our caching logic and results in duplicate model versions

###### *Implementation for single FPMaterialization* {#implementation-for-single-fpmaterialization}

* Fetches `FPMaterialization` from backend using a virtualenv python task.   
  * Materialization ID to retrieve is specified in DAG run conf  
  * Materialization configuration stored in as an XCOM value   
* Check if the materialization is already complete. If yes, skip to completion of DAG with no processing  
  * Completion state is determined by the `airflow_status` field equal to `success`  
* If materialization is not complete, set the deployment\_name (i.e. workspace of the DAG) and upload the materialization configuration to a S3 location  
  * Configuration is later retrieved inside a databricks job run using the UC API \- this is to avoid parameter size limits with the databricks jobs api  
  * airflow\_status is set to running [here](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/d2a96296aee71b2f7a866cc821ffa623e312db4c/freeport_airflow/dags/custom/webapp/freeport_service_operator.py#L469-L476)  
* Materialization job cluster size is determined via [databricks workflow](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/d2a96296aee71b2f7a866cc821ffa623e312db4c/freeport_databricks/workflows/cluster_sizing/00_scale_using_table_size.py)  
  * Workflow scans source table versions and query for materialization to size job cluster  
  * Cluster overrides can be specified via API at the FPModelVersion level \- if specified the FP-recommended cluster size is ignored  
* Materialization output tables are determined based on its configuration and corresponding databricks workflows are triggered  
  * A batch output table is always triggered ([workflow notebook](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/d2a96296aee71b2f7a866cc821ffa623e312db4c/freeport_databricks/workflows/materialization/01_materialize_fp_model_version_as_batch_table.py))  
  * If a changes\_table FPTarget is specified, the [changes table workflow](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/d2a96296aee71b2f7a866cc821ffa623e312db4c/freeport_databricks/workflows/materialization/02_materialize_fp_model_version_as_changes_table.py) is triggered in parallel  
    * The changes table logic includes generating the changed data records between the latest released table version vs. the current query results for the given source table versions  
  * If the model version has enable\_variants=True, a variants option workflow will be triggered  
    * This is a 2 step process \- first all of the unique variant options is determined based on the new batch table version and stored in a variant options table ([workflow](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/d2a96296aee71b2f7a866cc821ffa623e312db4c/freeport_databricks/workflows/materialization/03_materialize_fp_model_version_variant_options.py))  
    * The variant options are upserted into the Freeport database \- [custom python task](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/d2a96296aee71b2f7a866cc821ffa623e312db4c/freeport_airflow/dags/custom/webapp/variant_option_operator.py#L12) using spark connect  
  * Each of the output table workflows will exit with metadata about the FPTargetVersion delta table statistics \- these are used when saving the FPMaterialization at the end of the DAG  
* All of the workflow outputs are merged together and uploaded to the Freeport backend  
  * `FPMaterialization` airflow\_status is marked as success  
  * `FPTargetVersion` object is created based on the statistics from the workflow outputs  
  * A summary email of the materialization is emailed to freeport@  
* If the FPModel is enabled in dispatch a deferred publication is created in Dispatch via an API request  
  * **NOTE**: this step is skipped if FPMaterializationGroups are used, as the group is released via FPReleaseGroups which does not use deferred publications  
  * **NOTE**: deferred publications are not created if the FPMaterialization.allow\_release=False at the time of this step's execution  
* **NOTE**: There are number of "QA tasks" \- these are static tasks that are no-ops that will be removed/replaced when target table QA tests are implemented  
* If any task above fails, the FPMaterialization airflow\_status is set to failed and the dag run finishes

###### *Implementation for FPMaterializationGroup* {#implementation-for-fpmaterializationgroup}

* Fetches `FPMaterializationGroup` from backend using a virtualenv python task.   
  * Materialization Group ID to retrieve is specified in DAG run conf  
  * Materialization group configuration stored in as an XCOM value   
* If there is an earlier `FPMaterializationGroup` for a given FPModelGroup that is not yet complete/failed, the DAG run waits until those are complete  
  * This is needed to handle race conditions given how users might trigger creation of these groups repeatedly from Databricks  
* Start processing of the group  
  * Set group airflow\_status=running  
* Isolate each `FPMaterialization` configuration from the group and trigger a parallel, child DAG run for each \- same DAG to process as the individual FPMaterialization  
  * The Group DAG run waits for successful completion of each child dag run  
  * Each child dag run is triggered in order of the depends\_on value for the FPModelVersion of the FPMaterialization within the group. The associated target versions are resolved   
* Once all materialization DAG runs are complete, the FPMaterializationGroup and FPMaterialization airflow\_status is set to success  
  * This is important to establish a transaction-style behavior of these operations for release scheduling, i.e. the group is done when all the materialization are done and vice versa, and releases can't occur until then  
* If any task above fails or a child materialization dag run fails, the group airflow\_status is set to failed and the dag run finishes

###### *Common Errors* {#common-errors-1}

* FPTargetVersion already exists \- can be fixed by repairing the workflow job run tasks and having them re-run \- this will generate a new delta table version that will allow the FPTargetVersion to be valid and no longer a duplicate record  
* Spark job aborted errors \- usually resolved on automated retries, but workflow can be repaired to get a successful run. If the job continues to fail, using a different cluster via cluster overrides can help

###### *Implementation for single FPRelease* {#implementation-for-single-fprelease}

* Fetches `FPRelease` from the backend using a virtualenv python task.   
  * Model version ID and Materialization ID is used to retrieve the associated FPRelease via the DAG run conf  
  * Release configuration stored in as an XCOM value   
* Check if the release is already complete. If yes, skip to completion of DAG with no processing  
  * Completion state is determined by the `airflow_status` field equal to `success`  
* If release is not complete, set the deployment\_name (i.e. workspace of the DAG) and upload the release configuration to a S3 location  
  * Configuration is later retrieved inside a databricks job run using the UC API \- this is to avoid parameter size limits with the databricks jobs api  
  * airflow\_status is set to running [here](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/dded4e32d19648e45616c8e452771382450dee49/freeport_airflow/dags/custom/webapp/freeport_service_operator.py#L858-L872)  
* Launch databricks job run to create or updates prod catalog view to point to the release's staging table version of the associated fp materialization ([Notebook](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/dded4e32d19648e45616c8e452771382450dee49/freeport_databricks/workflows/release/01_create_or_replace_published_views.py))  
  * Each of the associated tables for a given materialization will have prod views created/updated (ex: batch table, changes table, variant table)  
  * PIT table will not be ready until the Audit Version DAG is updated (see below)  
* If the parent FPmodelVersion is variant enabled, then variant views are generated/refreshed via a job run ([Notebook](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/dded4e32d19648e45616c8e452771382450dee49/freeport_databricks/workflows/release/03_create_or_replace_variant_views.py))  
* Record the FPRelease as a success if it is not a PIT append table type.   
  * PIT deliverable FPReleases will still be in a "running" state until the Audit Version DAG run is complete  
  * NOTE: this logic will change once we separate PIT deliverables from the standard deliverable  
* If the FPModelVersion has a [`databricks_workflows_trigger`](https://freeport-service-prod.yipit.systems/admin/data_model/fptag/13/change/) tag, launch a workflow run of the associated Job IDs ([task](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/dded4e32d19648e45616c8e452771382450dee49/freeport_airflow/dags/custom/databricks/workflow_trigger_operator.py#L7))  
  * This is to support custom post-processing / workflows for a given product/team on release of a deliverable  
  * The KM grid on the portal depends on this trigger firing off for key metics deliverables  
* Trigger the AuditVersion DAG run for the given FPRelease

###### *Implementation for FPReleaseGroup* {#implementation-for-fpreleasegroup}

* Fetches `FPReleaseGroup` from backend using a virtualenv python task.   
  * Release Group ID to retrieve is specified in DAG run conf  
  * Release group configuration stored in as an XCOM value   
* Check if the release group is already complete. If yes, skip to completion of DAG with no processing  
  * Completion state is determined by the `airflow_status` field equal to `success`  
* If release group is not complete, set the deployment\_name (i.e. workspace of the DAG) and upload the release group configuration to a S3 location  
  * Configuration is later retrieved inside a databricks job run using the UC API \- this is to avoid parameter size limits with the databricks jobs api  
  * airflow\_status is set to running [here](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/dded4e32d19648e45616c8e452771382450dee49/freeport_airflow/dags/custom/webapp/freeport_service_operator.py#L1552-L1567)  
* Launch a databricks workflow to update all of the prod catalog views in the group to the release's corresponding staging table version ([notebook](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/dded4e32d19648e45616c8e452771382450dee49/freeport_databricks/workflows/release/04_create_or_replace_published_views_group.py))  
  * This is done in a single workflow to speed up release time   
* Parse out each FP Release into a separate config, this allows us to launch parallel sets of post-processing tasks for each release in this parent group dag  
* For each release, call the child release DAG  
  * This DAG is the same as the single release DAG but skips the job run step of updating the prod catalog view since it is already done  
  * Main steps here are to update variant views if variants are enabled  
  * Any databricks workflow triggers and audit version DAG runs are not done at this step  
* After the child release DAG is successful, marks the release group and child releases as a success  
  * If the release has PIT Table type, the status remains running until the audit version DAG run is completed  
  * This will remaining in a deferred i.e. waiting state in the group DAG   
* Final post-processing of each release is done by a parallel set of tasks  
  * Triggers databricks workflow runs if the [`databricks_workflows_trigger`](https://freeport-service-prod.yipit.systems/admin/data_model/fptag/13/change/) tag is set on the release's FPModelVersion  
  * Triggers Audit DAG run for each release  
  * Triggers Dispatch publication for each release to start fulfillments  
* If any child release fails or its post processing steps fails, the group is set to a failed state

###### *Implementation for single FPAuditVersion* {#implementation-for-single-fpauditversion}

* Fetches `FPRelease` from the backend using a virtualenv python task.   
  * Model version ID and Materialization ID is used to retrieve the associated FPRelease via the DAG run conf  
  * Release configuration stored in as an XCOM value   
* If release is not complete, set the deployment\_name (i.e. workspace of the DAG) and upload the release configuration to a S3 location  
  * Configuration is later retrieved inside a databricks job run using the UC API \- this is to avoid parameter size limits with the databricks jobs api  
* Audit version job cluster size is determined via [databricks workflow](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/d2a96296aee71b2f7a866cc821ffa623e312db4c/freeport_databricks/workflows/cluster_sizing/00_scale_using_table_size.py)  
  * Workflow scans staging table version size to size job cluster  
* Audit version workflow job ruin is triggered based on cluster size ([workflow notebook](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/dded4e32d19648e45616c8e452771382450dee49/freeport_databricks/workflows/release/02_create_or_replace_audit_table.py))  
  * If serverless flag is enabled, the cluster size is ignored since serverless autoscales on its own  
  * The audit table version is created/overwritten for each table of the deliverable  
  * For PIT append tables, the table version is an append operation instead of an overwrite to preserve PIT history  
  * For each audit table version, the correspond prod catalog view is updated to point to these \- this is done to avoid rely on the staging table version as it can be vacuumed away   
* Once the audit version tables are completed, the FPAuditVerison record is saved  
  * If it's a PIT append table type, the FPRelease status is also marked as a success

###### *Implementation for DAG* {#implementation-for-dag}

* Unlike other DAGs that are triggered via API, this will run every 5 minutes automatically  
* For single-deliverable releases not in Dispatch:  
  * Queries the Freeport backend for materializations:  
    * enabled\_in\_dispatch=False  
    * Not a member of a materialization group  
    * That are successful  
    * allow\_release=True  
    * FPRelease doesn't exist  
    * release\_timestamp \<= current time  
  * For each materialization creates an FPRelease record and triggers the FPRelease DAG run  
* For group release DAGs:  
  * Queries the Freeport backend for materialization groups:  
    * That are successful  
    * allow\_release=True  
    * FPReleaseGroup doesn't exist  
    * release\_timestamp \<= current time  
  * For each materialization group create the corresponding FPReleaseGroup record and child FPReleases. Trigger the group release DAG run as well

#### **Databricks**  {#databricks}

##### **Databricks Tables** {#databricks-tables}

* Freeport has dedicated catalogs where it creates/manages tables  
  * These catalogs are named with this convention: `yd_fp_<department_name>_(staging|prod|audit)`  
  * fsefe  
  * All tables/databases/catalogs are owned by PG\_FREEPORT  
  * Other PG groups are given read only access at the catalog level if the data access is needed for day to day work  
  * The database and table names will match in the staging, prod, and audit catalogs  
  * The **staging catalog** is where materializations are stored  
    * Delta table versions in this catalog are ready for release but not yet released  
    * Some table table versions may never be released  
  * The **prod catalog** is where the current released materialization is accessible  
    * This catalog is what Dispatch primarily uses to process fulfillments for client deliveries  
    * Only views exist in the prod catalog, they point to the corresponding materialization table version that was released in the Freeport API  
    * Once the audit table is populated, the views will point to the matching audit table version to avoid any issues with table retention / vacuuming of the staging catalog tables  
  * The audit catalog is where each released view is retained indefinitely as a persisted delta table version  
    * Each audit table version should map 1:1 to an FP release  
    * Table retention is indefinite unless otherwise specified in the model version configuration  
    * Audit tables should be source of truth of what content was released to clients and when  
* Databases in Freeport should follow standard naming conventions  
  * i.e. End in **\_gold** or **\_sandbox**, the freeport client in databricks validates this  
* Each deliverable should have a unique output table 

##### **Databricks Workflows** {#databricks-workflows}

* Workflows for Freeport are triggered as one-off, parameterized runs via Airflow (WorkflowOperator)  
* 

##### **Databricks Client** {#databricks-client}

* Freeport python client that databricks users should use to generate deliverables and materialize them  
* All users should use [v1 client](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/develop/freeport_databricks/client/v1.py) moving forward, underlying Freeport API should only be used by applications / advanced use cases (requires review)  
* The client wraps around Freeport APIs to make it easier to use in databricks  
  * Validates inputs upfront  
  * Handles polling logic automatically  
  * Renders dataframes for exploration of returned data

#### **Dispatch Interaction** {#dispatch-interaction}

##### **Deliverables** {#deliverables}

* Created / assigned when a Freeport deliverable / model version is successfully updated  
* Deliverables in Dispatch map to a Freeport model \+ data major version  
* The name of the deliverable in Dispatch will indicate this:  \<Model Version Title\> \[\<data\_major\_version:03\>\]  
* Deliverables need to be uniquely named and can get in a bad state if they are mapped incorrectly between Freeport and Dispatch  
* In the Freeport deliverable, there will be a model version tag for the dispatch deliverable ID

##### **Deferred Publications** {#deferred-publications}

* Created in Dispatch when:  
  * Materializations are successfully processed (last step of DAG)  
  * And allow\_release=True on the materialization  
  * And enable\_in\_dispatch=True on the associated model  
* Timestamp for publication will match release\_timestamp of materialization  
  * When materialization is updated for its schedule, dispatch will also be updated to keep schedule in sync

##### **Releases** {#releases}

* Dispatch will make an API call to create a Release in Freeport when the deferred publication release timestamp comes due  
  * This happens inside Dispatch's DAG  
  * The Dispatch DAG will then poll for completion until the Release reaches a success state  
* From there, Dispatch will use the Release's current views to process fulfillments   
  * Fulfillment logic varies based on the materialization type (ex: batch, changes, pit\_append)

### **Common Maintenance** {#common-maintenance}

#### **DAG Operations** {#dag-operations}

##### **Clearing a dag run** {#clearing-a-dag-run}

* Select a dag run from the grid view that needs to be retried by clicking on the top long bar for a run that indicates the total duration  
* You can confirm the dag run using the **details** tab of the run popup, scrolling to the bottom shows the run parameters that reference the FP application id the run is related to. 

  Example of the details tab: 

  ![][image1]

* Once you know the run to repair, click on a task (square below the top bar of the run) and in the popup click **Clear task**  
  ![][image2]  
* Confirm you want to proceed by clicking Clear on the next popup, and then the specific tasks will be retried   
* If the repaired run is successful, the `airflow_status` field in Django admin should be updated. Generally airflow tasks are safe to re-run, however actions that interact with external systems ex: Dispatch should be approached with caution if those tasks had already run successfully before the repaired run. In these cases, it may be that the Dispatch API fails with validation errors for trying to create duplicate records or an action had already been done

##### **Deleting a model or model group**  {#deleting-a-model-or-model-group}

* If there is a request to fully purge a model our model group and its associated tables then you can use a Freeport Django admin to trigger the delete operation  
* First confirm if there are any dispatch deliverables related to the models to be deleted. You can find these in the dispatch UI by searching in the deliverables tab for each model version title that is related to the FPModel or each FPModel in the FPModelGroup   
  * If there are dispatch deliverables associated, ask the dispatch team to delete these first.  
* Afterwards, select the model or model group in the Django admin list view. There is a search bar you can filter by slug in case you don’t see it in the list  
* In the Django admin actions dropdown, select delete the resource and its child tables. This is a custom command that will fire a custom Delete DAG run. Example of selecting the Django admin action 

  ![][image3]

* The DAG will permanently delete any tables and views associated to this FPModel across the staging/prod/audit catalogs. Afterwards it will delete the record and child records in the Freeport backend.   
  * For Model group DAGs this will delete the FPModelGroup record, the child FPModels of the group, all downstream child records of those models, and all associated tables of the models  
  * This is a **DANGEROUS** operation so only proceed if sure of what is being deleted. There are many cases when teams create bad deliverables where this admin action is needed. 

##### **Running a dag one off** {#running-a-dag-one-off}

* Each type of DAG (ex: Model Version, Materialization, ReleaseGroup, etc.) now has a one-off DAG queue. These DAGs have a special dag\_id with the suffix "**oneoff**".   
* These oneoff DAGs perform the same operations as the DAGs dedicated to each workspace, however, it will never be enqueued items by the Freeport API. As a result, they are idle and ready to go should there be any queue backups in the other DAGs.  
* You can fire off manual runs to process specific FP resources that are time sensitive during a queue backup through the Airflow UI. General steps:  
  * First, pause any DAGs that have a queue backup using the toggle found in the Freeport Airflow home page that lists all active DAGs. See the **blue toggle switch** on the left most column on this page:  
    ![][image4]

  * Once the slow DAGs are paused, identify in the Freeport Admin view the relevant FP resource IDs that need to be processed as a one-off.   
  * In the Freeport Airflow UI click on the play icon off to the far right for the appropriate one-off DAG. Ex: select "**fp\_data\_model\_materialization\_group\_one\_off**" if processing a FPMaterializationGroup as a one-off.  
    ![][image5]

  * A popup should show up asking to enter the DAG parameters for the run. This is where the FP resource IDs should be entered. Once the ID is entered, click Trigger.![][image6]  
  * The DAG run should be kicked off. Assuming the other DAGs are paused, the run should turn light green and start running right away.  
  * If the DAG run in the original DAG/queue gets processed as the queue clears, it should generally be ok. In most cases, Freeport DAGs have logic to detect this automatically and avoid reprocessing a record twice by skipping all of the tasks in the run.

#### **Serverless Feature Flags** {#serverless-feature-flags}

Freeport is using serverless relatively aggressively. Because it is a new databricks feature, it may be necessary to temporarily disable serverless during an outage. To do this, use the Posthog feature flags in [Production](https://us.posthog.com/project/85053/feature_flags)

* In Posthog, click on the feature flags tab for the **Freeport \- Production** project. This controls the flags for the production installation of Airflow  
* There are flags for each type of DAG or databricks task. Ex: Separate feature flags for materializations or release groups. Depending on the nature of the outage, you have the flexibility to disable serverless for all or some DAGs using the dropdown options to the right of each Flag in the UI.

	![][image7]

* Once the flag(s) are disabled, any failed DAG runs should be [repaired](#clearing-a-dag-run). A retry will now use a classic job cluster or interactive cluster if the workload is small.   
  * DAG runs that are active and waiting for a retry, should also respect the flag value on subsequent attempts  
* When the incident is resolved, simply toggle the flags back on. Subsequent DAG runs should now use serverless again.

#### **Monitoring** {#monitoring}

##### **Airflow Alert Emails** {#airflow-alert-emails}

* Make sure to read through emails that have subjects starting with **\[⚓ Freeport Airflow Error ⚓\]**  
* If the email bodies indicate the task state is "failed", then there are no more retries and the DAG run is considered a failure   
  * These will usually indicate some corrective actions needs to happen  
  * Common failures that require user action and is not a systematic error:  
    * **fp\_data\_model\_versioning** **DAGs**: when the `versioning_tasks.generate_fields` task fails. Usually this is a configuration issue with the query template \+ parameters \+ input tables not working together  
    * **Fp\_dq\_source\_version\_test\_run DAGs** (AutoQA): If the process test databricks workflow run fails for a `ConcurrentAppendException`, this is a known issue and usually resolves itself on retries  
    * **All Data Model DAGs**:   
      * Transient databricks issues including:  
        * Cannot reach driver error  
        * ShuffleFetchFailed error  
        * Transient issues when the all purpose or job cluster is overloaded. This is becoming less often now that we are using serverless, and should be successful on a retry attempt unless there is some outsized job required to run. 

##### **Django Admin** {#django-admin}

* The Admin UI can be a helpful place to look for failed or running FP resources. For the given model, use the preset filters off to the right that filters for specific Airflow states.  
  * Freeport currently only registers the success, running, and failed states in Django. The other states will not be tracked or discoverable.  
* If looking for runs that have been queued in airflow but not started, the databricks\_job\_run\_url and/or the airflow\_url columns will be blank. Seeing many of these records can indicate a queue backup.

##### **Critical Feeds** {#critical-feeds}

* Monitor airflow alert emails for materialization and/or model version failures. **Subject line: \[⚓ Freeport Airflow Error ⚓\]**   
  **![][image8]**  
  *Example airflow error email*

  * Alerts are sent to the **\#freeport-notifications** channel for databricks failures from Freeport airflow runs  
* If there are transient errors on critical feeds, resolved them by "**clearing"** the Airflow run to rerun failed tasks:  
  * Follow the **Airflow Worker Logs** link in the error email.   
    * Can also use this [SQL query](https://yipitdata-product.cloud.databricks.com/sql/editor/e0c85ee9-2e83-44f2-ab0c-f6fc356c0f1d?o=2498774132964769) or the [django admin](https://freeport-service-prod.yipit.systems/admin/data_model/fpmaterialization/) page to search by materialization ID and get the airflow run url.   
  * Go the "**Grid**" tab, and click on the task that is failing (*outlined red or yellow*)  
    ![][image9]

  * Click **Clear task**. Downstream and recursive options should be selected \- defaults. There is a dropdown to see all of the tasks that will be retried if helpful to confirm.  
    ![][image10]

  * On the confirmation dialog, click **Clear** again. The airflow tasks should be cleared, and start running within a few minutes (outlined light green)

* If errors are not transient, more investigation is needed in the databricks job run to understand and fix the root cause. Potential issues:

| Potential Issue | Options to Fix |
| :---- | :---- |
| Upstream table schema changed that is incompatible with the query template | Restore the original schema in the upstream table.  Generate a new query template version and use that version in generating a new model version. The model version (deliverable) can then be materialized and released |
| Code issues the Freeport databricks workflow | Open a PR to fix the databricks workflow code errors and merge to develop, and then main.  Clear the failing airflow tasks, the new version of workflow code should be picked up from main branch |
| Changes in spark behavior that impacts the query template | Generate a new query template version and use that version in generating a new model version. The model version (deliverable) can then be materialized and released |
| Cluster configuration issues | Generate a new model version with custom cluster settings (`databricks_cluster_overrides`) if the defaults are not working. The model version (deliverable) can then be materialized and released The cluster overrides field in Freeport will use the FLEXIBLE cluster policy when processing materializations and add/override the policy via any settings defined the field |

#### **Deployments** {#deployments}

##### **Setting up Freeport in Databricks Workspace** {#setting-up-freeport-in-databricks-workspace}

* Create 3 catalogs in the workspace if new catalogs are needed for the relevant business unit(s)  
  * These should be named `yd_fp_{business_unit}_staging`,  `yd_fp_{business_unit}_prod`,  `yd_fp_{business_unit}_audit`  
  * Catalogs should follow general access standards:  
    * Be owned by `PG_ADMIN`  
    * Add comments to catalog (see other FP catalogs for examples)  
    * Grant `PG_FREEPORT` read/write access at catalog level  
    * Grant business unit PG groups in the workspace read only access  
  * Restrict these catalogs if the workspace is sensitive, consult DPE on this   
* Add the Freeport PG to the workspace  
  * [YDBM Script to create PG Group](https://github.com/Yipit/yipit_databricks_maintenance/blob/develop/yipit_databricks_maintenance/administration/identity_management/group/01_create_permission_groups.py)   
  * Scope should be `FREEPORT`, group should be `PG_FREEPORT`  
  * The bucket names and instance profile are placeholder fields (use s3://yipit-freeport-dev and product instance profile). These are not used due to Unity Catalog.  
  * Store the `SP_FREEPORT` API token in the relevant 1Password secure note for the workspace  
  * Grant read/only access to relevant catalogs/databases that workspace users will be using in producing deliverables. Consult DPE to handle this administration.  
* Create a Freeport all purpose cluster and create cluster policies for Freeport  
  * If the PG group has been added to the workspace above, running the [Cluster Policies Deployment](https://yipitdata-de-production.cloud.databricks.com/?o=1347024889363018#job/223686958574758) workflow should generate this. Consult DPE for permission to run this.  
    * [Job Cluster Policies](https://github.com/Yipit/data_platform_policies/blob/develop/data_platform_policies/jobs/publish_cluster_policies/01a_publish_job_cluster_policies.py)   
    * [All Purpose Policies](https://github.com/Yipit/data_platform_policies/blob/develop/data_platform_policies/jobs/publish_cluster_policies/01b_publish_all_purpose_cluster_policies.py)   
  * `PG_FREEPORT` should be granted restart access on the cluster  
  * Add the correct **cost\_component\_name** tag, should be `freeport_<workspace_name>_delivery`, (ex: freeport\_investor\_delivery) see other Freeport all purpose clusters for convention  
* Create the Freeport Repo in a `ETL_Production` folder in the workspace   
  * Give Freeport and Workspace PG groups view access on the folder  
* Add a slack notification destination in the workspace  
  * Name should be **freeport-notifications**  
  * The slack webhook URL will need to be obtained from the slack web page  
* Update the [`FreeportAirflowApp`](https://pancakesui.yipit.systems/stacks/ca72dad6-ccbd-43ae-a4be-d5a6ace89c9f) pancakes stack for the following environment variables:  
  * Set a `AIRFLOW_CONN_<DEPLOYMENT_NAME>` variable. DEPLOYMENT\_NAME should be the workspace deployment name (use underscores instead of dashes)  
  * Update the `AIRFLOW__FREEPORT_DATABRICKS__ALL_PURPOSE_CLUSTER_ID` JSON. The Key should be the workspace deployment name. The value should be the all purpose cluster id in the workspace  
  * Update the `AIRFLOW__FREEPORT_DATABRICKS__NOTIFICATION_DESTINATION` environment variable, the key should be the workspace deployment name and the value should be the connection ID for the slack notification destination created. Click on the copy logo when viewing the destination settings in the workspace.  
* Update the `.circleci/config.yml` in the `freeport_service` repo to deploy the repo to the workspace  
  * Follow the same format as the other [workspaces in the file](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/5efee967e505628a92980a4aecacee2f89c017de/.circleci/config.yml#L581-L593)   
  * Replace repo\_id in the yml file with repo id generated in new workspace (check repo settings in databricks)

#### **Query Templates** {#query-templates}

##### **Updating Query Templates** {#updating-query-templates}

* Use the [get\_or\_create\_query\_template](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/827cc8727f5625595a74feff63518180d7b7cca7/freeport_databricks/client/v1.py#L846) client function to upload a new query template version.   
* Use the description field to note the changes for the new query template version  
* If a query template slug already exists, but the query template string has changed, a new version is created automatically in the backend  
  * Slugs can be found in the [Django admin](https://freeport-service-prod.yipit.systems/admin/data_model/fpquerytemplate/) for reference  
* Reference the new query template version ID in other Freeport client deliverable calls as needed

##### **Query Template Development** {#query-template-development}

* Use the [df\_from\_query\_template](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/827cc8727f5625595a74feff63518180d7b7cca7/freeport_databricks/client/v1.py#L988) or [sql\_from\_query\_template](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/blob/827cc8727f5625595a74feff63518180d7b7cca7/freeport_databricks/client/v1.py#L1044) function(s) to develop query templates.  
  * The sql function can be useful to validate the Output SQL text is as expected for various parameter inputs  
  * The df function can be useful to run queries on top of the output sql to validate data results

#### **Dispatch Interactions** {#dispatch-interactions}

There are a number of interaction points between Freeport and Dispatch, and is generally specific to each DAG view. See the below table to understand the relationships between the service:

| FP Model | FP DAG interaction | Dispatch resources affected |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| FPModelVersions and FPModelVersionGroups | The DAG upon successful processing of a FPModelVersion will create a Deliverable in Dispatch. The title for the deliverable in Dispatch matches the *FPModelVersion title \+ Data Major Version*  The FP DAG will trigger the Dispatch API to create the deliverable.  Patch or minor versions in Freeport will update the existing deliverable in Dispatch instead of creating a new one.  Major version changes will create new deliverables in Dispatch.  | Dispatch Deliverables are created or updated through these DAG runs.  If a FPModel is deleted the associated Dispatch deliverable should also be deleted. A possible issue is a FPModelVersion has a title that overlaps in Dispatch with another deliverable's title. This will create a failure in the FP model version DAG. Using a different title or deleting the duplicate deliverable can resolve the issue |
| FPMaterializations (non-group) | The DAG upon successful processing of a materialization will create a deferred publication record in Dispatch. These can be seen in the Dispatch UI under the "Scheduled Publications" tab of the UI  | Dispatch will retain scheduled publications and keep checking if the release time has come due.  When the publication is due, Dispatch will create an FPRelease via Freeport's API, which kicks off a release DAG run. Dispatch will wait for the FPRelease to finish processing to kick off customer fulfillments. While not in the DAG, patches to the Freeport materialization via API will change the schedule of the publication in Dispatch. If allow\_release is set to False, the scheduled publication is removed in Dispatch automatically  |
| FPRelease (non-groups) | N/A \- Freeport does not interact with Dispatch directly in this DAG. See the above materialization DAG for details of this behavior | If for some reason the FPRelease gets into a failed state, it is important to repair these runs to resolve the issue. It is likely the associated Dispatch DAG related to this release must be repaired, the dispatch team can do this if given the FP Release ID |
| FPReleaseGroups | The DAG will create publications for each FPRelease of the group after successful processing in the DAG run These are not deferred publications, instead it tells Dispatch to start fulfillments right away. | Dispatch will execute fulfillments for publications as soon as they are created. |

### **Development** {#development}

#### **Databricks Development Setup** {#databricks-development-setup}

* Pull [freeport\_service](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/tree/develop) repo from github into databricks  
* Check out into feature branch  
* Create a "scratch" folder at the root of the repo to store any development notebooks (the folder is git ignored and a safe space for testing functions)

  ![][image11]

* Grant personal repo view access to the service principal of attached cluster and the SP\_FREEPORT service principal (if not on shared mode)  
* **WARNING**:   
  * When in databricks the freeport\_service and freeport\_airflow modules will not be available. Those are only accessible during local development (see below)  
  * This is due to the package requirements of django and airflow not in databricks.  
* **WARNING**:  
  * When attempting to merge from a PR created in databricks, pre-commit checks may fail  
  * The current fix is to pull the branch into your local development environment and run make pre\_commit. This should fix any pre-commit related formatting issues. Commit the change files and push up to the branch. Once the checks pass you are safe to merge assuming you have PR approvals

#### **Local Development Setup** {#local-development-setup}

* First, set up personal repo folders in relevant databricks workspaces, give PG\_FREEPORT view access to repo  
* Clone the [freeport\_service](https://github.com/Yipit/freeport_service/tree/develop) repo into your local environment  
* Create a virtualenv (python 3.11) for freeport\_service and run `make setup` and `make setup-airflow` in the virtualenv  
* Create .env file at the project root directory, add required environment variables to run docker installation  
  * Ask for 1Pass access to the environment variables to copy over into your repo  
  * Adjust `AIRFLOW__FREEPORT_DATABRICKS__WORKSPACE_BASE_FOLDER` environment variable to be your personal Repo folder path  
  * The .env file is gitignored so secrets are not committed into the repo accidentally  
* Install [docker for desktop](https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/) if you do not already have it  
  * Ensure your docker app has enough memory and resources. Go to the docker desktop settings console and give at least 10Gb ram and min \~40Gb disk space for containers and images, assuming your machine has the specs available (M1+ should be ok)  
  * You will need to log in with your yipitdata docker account (we have an enterprise account)  
* Ensure your local environment has access to the LOCALSHOP environment variable (should be your Jfrog URL to access our internal libraries)  
* Create a scratch folder in your local environment (similar to the databrick setup above)  
  * Download the [3 seed JSON files](https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1LrmdGHm_cSpo-Kr2Ds9bsx1k5ae_OT9a) and put them in your local environment.   
  * These seed files will populate your database with records to get up and running faster  
* Run make setup-docker to build the docker images  
* Setup the Freeport Service (webapp database)   
  * Run `make migrate` to apply all active database migrations  
  * Run `make django-bash-docker`. It should open a terminal process you can interact with (this is a useful command to access the django shell when working locally)  
  * In the new shell prompt run the following commands:

```
# (ex: scratch/seed_fp_user.json)
python manage.py loaddata <relative path to user seed file> 
python manage.py loaddata <relative path to dm seed file> 
python manage.py loaddata <relative path to dq seed file> 

# Then create your django admin account 
# you will be prompted for a username (email) and password 
python manage.py createsuperuser --settings=freeport_service.settings
```

  * Exit the docker shell using ctrl+c  
  * Run make run-webapp to run just the freeport service API  
  * Log into the django admin page at: [**http://0.0.0.0:8000/admin**](http://0.0.0.0:8000/admin) using your credentials  
  * Exit the docker process using ctrl+c  
* Setup the Freeport Airflow (airflow database)  
  * Run `make airflow-setup-docker`. It should run a container to setup initial airflow resources  
  * Run `make airflow-shell-docker`. It should open a terminal process you can interact with (this is a useful command to access airflow installation when working locally)  
  * In the new shell prompt run the following commands:

```
airflow db migrate
```

  * Exit the docker shell using ctrl+c  
  * Run `make run-docker` to run the full application system  
  * Log into the airflow admin page at: [**http://0.0.0.0:8080**](http://0.0.0.0:8080/) using "airflow" as the username and password. This is the airflow console you can visit for local execution of DAGs  
  * Turn off the internal release scheduling dag as it is not needed for development \- it runs on a 5 min interval draining resources  
  * Exit the docker process using ctrl+c  
* Should be complete with local setup, moving forward  
  * Use `make run-docker` to start the docker installation anytime in the future and ctrl+c to exit the docker installation  
  * It is connected to your local project repo via volumes, any code changes made there will be automatically synced to running containers

#### **Unit Tests** {#unit-tests}

* Run `make test` in local environment to run all tests for the Freeport service webapp  
* It does not need access to a container installation to execute

#### **Integration Tests** {#integration-tests}

* Use the test Dags in the Airflow installation to trigger runs that connect to the Freeport API locally and then calls Freeport Airflow DAG runs

#### **Production Tests** {#production-tests}

* Feed deliverables should be automatically generated in Dispatch through the materialization process in Freeport  
  * SE or EI will need to go in for each deliverable and configure product information, s3 path, and snowflake views
